                    <tr><td class="ds-link">David Okonkwo</td><td class="ds-val">2</td><td class="ds-val">4</td><td class="ds-val">4</td><td><span class="seg-badge seg-atrisk">At Risk</span></td><td class="ds-val">$5,000</td><td style="color:#dc2626">&darr; last gift 9mo ago</td></tr>
                </tbody></table>
            </div>
        </div>

        <p>The RFM scoring system automatically identifies which mid-level donors are Champions (high recency, frequency, and monetary &mdash; your stewardship priorities), which are Loyal (consistent and reliable &mdash; your upgrade candidates), and which are At Risk (recency declining despite strong history &mdash; your recovery priorities). You can filter by giving range, sort by any score dimension, and export targeted lists for outreach.</p>

        <p>You can also ask the AI assistant directly: <em>&ldquo;Show me mid-level donors whose giving has increased for three consecutive years&rdquo;</em> or <em>&ldquo;Which mid-level donors haven&rsquo;t been contacted in the last 90 days?&rdquo;</em> The segmentation becomes actionable intelligence, not just a static report.</p>

        <h2>The Compounding Effect: Why Mid-Level Strategy Pays Off Exponentially</h2>

        <p>The ROI of a mid-level program isn&rsquo;t just about retaining $1,000&ndash;$10,000 donors at their current level (though that alone justifies the investment). It&rsquo;s about three compounding effects that build over time:</p>

        <ol>
            <li><strong>Retention savings.</strong> Mid-level donors who feel known and valued retain at significantly higher rates than those treated as part of the mass. Even a 5-percentage-point improvement in mid-level retention &mdash; from 60% to 65% &mdash; can represent tens of thousands of dollars in preserved revenue annually.</li>
            <li><strong>Upgrade acceleration.</strong> A dedicated mid-level program increases the rate at which donors move into major gift territory by 200&ndash;350x. If you have 300 mid-level donors, the difference between 0.5% and 4% upgrading is the difference between 1&ndash;2 new major donors per year and 12.</li>
            <li><strong>Legacy giving.</strong> With 31% of mid-level donors already including bequests and another 23% considering it, a mid-level program that includes planned giving conversations is building a future revenue stream that could dwarf current giving. Charitable bequests totaled $45.84 billion in the U.S. in 2024 &mdash; 7.7% of all charitable giving.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="art-callout-green art-callout">
            <strong>The math in action:</strong> A foundation with 300 mid-level donors averaging $3,500 each generates $1.05M annually from this segment. Improving retention by 5 points preserves roughly $52,500 per year. Upgrading 4% (12 donors) to major gifts at an average of $15,000 adds $180,000. And the planned giving pipeline being cultivated today will generate returns for decades. The mid-level program doesn&rsquo;t just pay for itself &mdash; it becomes the engine that drives sustainable growth across every level of giving.
        </div>

        <h2>Getting Started: Your First 90 Days</h2>

        <p>You don&rsquo;t need to build a perfect mid-level program overnight. Start with these four actions in your first 90 days:</p>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Week 1: Pull the list.</strong> Identify every donor in your mid-level range. Use RFM scoring to segment them by engagement level. How many do you have? What&rsquo;s their retention rate? What&rsquo;s the total revenue at stake?</li>
            <li><strong>Week 2&ndash;4: Call your top 50.</strong> Not to ask for money. Call to say thank you, share an impact update, and ask what matters to them. You&rsquo;ll learn more from 50 phone calls than from any amount of data analysis.</li>
            <li><strong>Month 2: Build the track.</strong> Create a distinct communication plan for mid-level donors &mdash; separate from your annual fund cadence. Map out 3&ndash;4 touchpoints for the next quarter: one impact report, one personal check-in, one insider update, and one thoughtful solicitation.</li>
            <li><strong>Month 3: Measure and adjust.</strong> Track retention, upgrade rates, and engagement depth. Compare mid-level donors who received personalized outreach to those who didn&rsquo;t. The data will make the case for expanding the program.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The mid-level donor gap exists in almost every foundation. It&rsquo;s not because organizations don&rsquo;t care about these donors &mdash; it&rsquo;s because the traditional fundraising structure creates a blind spot between mass-market annual giving and high-touch major gifts. Closing that gap doesn&rsquo;t require a revolution. It requires recognition that your most loyal, most capable, most upgrade-ready donors are already in your database, already giving generously, and already waiting for someone to treat them like the supporters they are.</p>

